---------------------------------------------------------------------------
An instance variable is a variable that is associated with an instance of a class. Unlike static variables,
instance variables are defined in a class but outside any method and are specific to each object of that class.
This means that each object has its own copy of an instance variable, so changes to the variable in one
object do not affect other objects. Instance variables are commonly used to store the state of an object.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Inheritance
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Inheritance allows one class to acquire the properties and methods of another class.

ğŸ‘‰ The class that is inherited from = Parent/Super Class
ğŸ‘‰ The class that inherits = Child/Sub Class

This helps in:

Code reusability

Reducing duplication

Building real- world relationships (Car â†’ SportsCar)

Types of Inheritance in Java

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Java supports:

Single inheritance

Multilevel inheritance

Hierarchical inheritance

(Java does NOT support multiple inheritance using classes.)

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

What is super keyword?

super is used to refer to immediate parent class.

You use super for:

Calling parent class constructor

Accessing parent class variables

Calling parent class methods

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How super is used here?
Usage	                     Example	                Meaning
Call parent constructor	     super(brand, speed)	    Initializes parent fields
Access parent method	     super.display()	        Runs Car's display()
Access parent variables	     super.brand (if needed)	Gets parentâ€™s value


