-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Runtime Polymorphism (Dynamic Polymorphism)

Runtime polymorphism occurs when a method is called based on the object's actual type at runtime, not the reference type.

ğŸ‘‰ Achieved using method overriding
ğŸ‘‰ Decided by JVM during program execution (runtime)
ğŸ‘‰ Supports flexibility and extensibility


Dynamic Method Dispatch
Dynamic Method Dispatch is the mechanism that enables runtime polymorphism.

It means: When a parent class reference points to a child class object, the overridden method of the child class is executed.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

constructor overloading and methode overloading fall under compile time polymorphism


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

| Feature       | Compile-time Polymorphism                         | Runtime Polymorphism        |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Also called   | Early binding                                     | Late binding                |
| Decision time | Compile time                                      | Runtime                     |
| Achieved by   | Method **Overloading**                            | Method **Overriding**       |
| Inheritance   | Not required                                      | Required                    |
| Parameters    | Must be different                                 | Must be same                |
| Return type   | Can be same or different                          | Must be same (or covariant) |
| Speed         | Faster                                            | Slightly slower             |
| Flexibility   | Less flexible                                     | More flexible               |
| Example       | `add(int a, int b)` vs `add(int a, int b, int c)` | Parent ref â†’ Child object   |

